
[1]stanch

   STANCH, v.t. In a general sense, to stop; to set or fix; but applied
   only to the blood; to stop the flowing of blood. Cold applications to
   the neck will often stanch the bleeding of the nose.

   STANCH, v.i. To stop, as blood; to cease to flow.

   Immediately the issue of her blood stanched. Luke 8.

    STANCH, a. [This is the same word as the foregoing, the primary sense
              of which is to set; hence the sense of firmness.]

   1. Sound; firm; strong and tight; as a stanch ship.

   2. Firm in principle; steady; constant and zealous; hearty; as a stanch
   churchman; a stanch republican; a stanch friend or adherent.

   In politics I hear youre stanch.

   3. Strong; not to be broken.

   4. Firm; close.

   This is to be kept stanch.

   A stanch hound, is one that follows the scent closely without error or
   remissness.
